I also spun up a Java solution using the EWS java jar.  I havn't spent much time working in Python or with EWS, so may be some ignorance on my part, but the Java API and the Python one seem quite different.  For my current problem, a Python solution is prefereable for integration with some other Python scripts used to process emails once they are extracted.  I just spun un the Java solution to help see if that might help identify the source as either our Exchange server or a bug in the Python library.  In any case, the Java solution worked successfully right away.  I tweaked an example I found via Google, and here's the important bits:
```
    public void  readEmails() {
        boolean more = true;
        int i = 1;
        try {
            Folder folder = Folder.bind(service, WellKnownFolderName.SentItems);
            ItemView view = new ItemView(NUMBER_EMAILS_FETCH);

            while(more) {
                FindItemsResults<Item> results = service.findItems(folder.getId(), view);
                for (Item item : results) {
                    Map messageData = readEmailItem(item.getId());
                    System.out.println( String.format("%d \"%s\" from %s", i++, messageData.get("subject"), messageData.get("senderName") ) );
                }
                more = results.isMoreAvailable();
                if (more)
                {
                    view.setOffset(results.getNextPageOffset());
                }
            }
        } catch (Exception e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
```

