@chriddyp  Is there a possibility to make `n_clicks_timestamp` equal `-1` or `0` by default for all buttons or even all components? Now before comparing values in callback one has to check if it is `None` (default) and then adapt comparison based on it or set it to `0` if it is `None`. 

The way you specified in example about explicitly setting it to `-1` in the component constructor call is cumbersome and requires modifying all layouts where one wants to use that new functionality.

Simply making that property equal to `0` by default would solve it.

Oh wow, so in working on the latest topic branch (latest version in #43), I ended up running into the same issue, and also ended up finding @patricksnape's fix.  You'll find my "discovery" [here](https://github.com/scikit-build/scikit-build/pull/38#issuecomment-228079982) (complete with a mini-rant).

Based on the CMake mailing list [link](https://cmake.org/pipermail/cmake/2009-October/032520.html) in that comment, I had believed that this was a Visual Studio problem.  But taking a closer look at your discussion [here](https://github.com/msarahan/conda-build/commit/a236bdbb80f3eba15eff2538c7a79d7dff0aabc6), it looks like I just don't know enough about the details of Visual Studio and its Python support.

